            factOption.put("hardcoded_Biology", "Biology is the scientific study of life and living organisms, encompassing various fields, including botany, zoology, and microbiology.; The cell is the basic unit of life, and all living organisms are composed of one or more cells.; DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, carries the genetic information for all living things and determines traits.; The human body contains approximately 37.2 trillion cells, which work together to maintain life.; Photosynthesis is the process by which plants convert sunlight into energy, producing oxygen as a byproduct.; There are more than 8.7 million known species of organisms on Earth, with many more yet to be discovered.; The largest living organism is a fungus in Oregon, covering about 2,385 acres and estimated to be over 2,400 years old.; The term \"biodiversity\" refers to the variety of life on Earth and is crucial for ecosystem health and resilience.; The average human has about 60,000 miles of blood vessels in their body, enough to circle the Earth more than twice.; Insects make up about 75% of all known animal species, showcasing the vast diversity within this group.; The mitochondrion, often called the \"powerhouse of the cell,\" produces energy in the form of ATP.; The human brain has approximately 86 billion neurons, making it one of the most complex structures in the known universe.; A group of lions is called a \"pride,\" while a group of flamingos is known as a \"flamboyance.\"; The study of living organisms at the molecular level is known as molecular biology, which examines interactions between various cellular systems.; The world's oldest known living organism is a bristlecone pine tree estimated to be over 5,000 years old.; The study of the interactions between organisms and their environment is known as ecology.; Human beings share about 60% of their DNA with bananas, highlighting the shared genetic material across species.; The heart of a blue whale, the largest animal on Earth, can weigh as much as a small car, about 400 pounds.; The Galápagos Islands were crucial to Charles Darwin's theory of evolution and natural selection.; Coral reefs, often referred to as the \"rainforests of the sea,\" support diverse marine life and are vital to ocean ecosystems.; The process of evolution explains how species adapt to their environments over time through natural selection.; The immune system is a complex network of cells, tissues, and organs that work together to defend the body against pathogens.; Bacteria are the most abundant organisms on Earth and can be found in nearly every habitat, including extreme environments.; Human beings have approximately 20,000 protein-coding genes, which contribute to various biological functions.; The study of animal behavior is known as ethology, which explores how animals interact with their environment and each other.; The average human takes about 20,000 breaths a day, providing oxygen for cellular respiration.; Fungi play a crucial role in ecosystems by decomposing organic matter and recycling nutrients.; The fastest land animal is the cheetah, capable of running speeds up to 75 miles per hour in short bursts.; The process of genetic variation is essential for evolution and occurs through mutations and recombination.; Insects communicate using pheromones, which are chemical signals that trigger specific behaviors.; The structure of DNA was discovered by James Watson and Francis Crick in 1953, revealing its double-helix shape.; The smallest known living organism is a type of bacteria called Mycoplasma, which can be as small as 0.2 micrometers.; The process of mitosis allows cells to divide and reproduce, ensuring growth and repair in multicellular organisms.; The human body has around 206 bones, which provide structure and protect vital organs.; The concept of symbiosis refers to the close interaction between different species, which can be mutualistic, commensalistic, or parasitic.; The study of genetics examines how traits are inherited from one generation to the next through genes.; The largest organ in the human body is the skin, which serves as a protective barrier against environmental threats.; The circulatory system, powered by the heart, is responsible for transporting oxygen, nutrients, and waste throughout the body.; The chemical reactions that occur within living organisms to maintain life are known as metabolism.; The human body has five senses: sight, hearing, touch, taste, and smell, allowing us to perceive our environment.; The discovery of antibiotics, such as penicillin, has significantly impacted medicine and the treatment of bacterial infections.; All living organisms require water to survive, as it plays a vital role in biochemical reactions.; The study of plant life is known as botany, which includes the examination of plant structure, function, and ecology.");
